Air freight into Europe by Nigerian carriers and other global airlines has assumed a new dimension as the regional bloc – the European Union (EU) – now requires that airlines submit advance cargo information by completing an Entry Summary Declaration (ENS) form. This policy would affect Nigeria’s airlines, including Allied Air, Cargo Lux and other African carriers that lift cargo from the Lagos, Abuja, Kano and Port Harcourt airports into Europe. The new policy, which takes effect from March 2, next year is put together under the second phase of the EU’s new customs pre- arrival security and safety programme termed – Import Control Systems 2 (ICS2) Release 2.   Bill to increase retirement age for people with disability…     Alleged fraud: Okorocha seeks court’s permission to travel…     Fintiri picks female VC as running mate   In an industry travel advisory, the EU said it is mandatory for freight forwarders, air carriers, express couriers, and postal operators transporting goods to or through the EU, including Norway and Switzerland, will be required to comply with the new directive. According to the EU, economic operators involved in handling, sending, shipping and transporting cargo, express or postal consignments to or via the EU by air, have to comply with new advance data reporting requirements for pre-loading and pre-arrival customs risk assessments. By collecting data on goods entering the EU prior to their loading and arrival, supports effective risk-based customs controls, while facilitating free flow of legitimate trade across the EU’s external borders. The EU said ICS2 will simplify the movement of goods between Customs offices at the first point of entry and final destination in the EU, adding that ICS2 will streamline requests for additional information and pre-departure risk screening by Customs authorities.